sec.p:
Static optimization: Estimates the muscle activations ( \alpha α) producing a given \tau τ (Anderson & Pandy, 2001). It minimizes the muscle activation p-norm ( p p usually being 2 2) that matches a given \tau τ using nonlinear optimization (Ipopt, Wächter & Biegler, 2006).
\begin{aligned} & \underset{\alpha \in \mathbb{R}^m}{\text{minimize}} & & \left\lVert\alpha\right\rVert_p \\ & \text{subject to} & & \tau_{mus_i}(\alpha ,q, \dot{q}) - \tau_{kin_i}(q, \dot{q}, \ddot{q}) = 0, &\; i=1,\ldots,n \\ & & & 0 \leq \alpha_{t_j} \leq 1, &\; j=1,\ldots,m \end{aligned}
minimizeα∈ℝm∥α∥psubject toτmusi(α,q,q̇)−τkini(q,q̇,q̈)=0,i=1,…,n0≤αtj≤1,j=1,…,m where \tau_{mus_i}(\alpha ,q, \dot{q}) τmusi(α,q,q̇) and \tau_{kin_i}(q, \dot{q}, \ddot{q}) τkini(q,q̇,q̈) are \tau τ computed from muscle forces ( F_{mus}(\alpha, q, \dot{q}) Fmus(α,q,q̇)) and inverse dynamics, respectively.
